# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: absorption-refrigerator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] An **absorption-compression heat pump** (**ACHP**) is a device that integrate an electric compressor in an absorption heat pump.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In some cases this is obtained by combining a vapor-compression heat pump and an absorption heat pump.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] It is also referred to as a hybrid heat pump which is however a broader field.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Thanks to this integration, the device can obtain cooling and heating effects using both thermal and electrical energy sources.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This type of systems is well coupled with cogeneration systems where both heat and electricity are produced.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Depending on the configuration, the system can maximize heating and cooling production from a given amount of fuel, or can improve the temperature (hence the quality) of waste heat from other processes.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This second use is the most studied one and has been applied to several industrial applications.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The first absorption-compression heat pump cycle concept was patented by Osenbrück.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Little research on it was done in the following years.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] in the 70s, the energy saving potential of the cycle grew in interest and there was a rapid increase in research activities in the field.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In this period several experimental plants were built and in 1997, Groll summarized this activities in its review where he identified more than 40 studies.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] At that time, considerable work was still needed before the ACHP could become commercially available.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Nordtvedt studied the cycle in his doctoral thesis and his studies ended up in the construction, in 2011, of the first commercial application in the Norwegian Food Industry.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] After this, several units have been installed for commercial use in various high temperature industrial applications.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantage with respect to compression heat pump is that the compression-absorption heat pumps allow the heat to be transfer with a temperature glide.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The compression heat pump uses a single pure working fluid, hence exchanges heat at a constant temperature.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption-compression heat pump uses instead a binary mixture where the condensation and evaporation occur with a temperature glide.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This property increases the efficiency of the heat transfer when the heat source also has a significant temperature glide, which is the typical condition found when dealing with waste heat recovery.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Being a hybrid solution that can exploit both heat and mechanical/electric energy sources, the device can be perfectly coupled with cogeneration units to produce heating and cooling at very high efficiencies.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Moreover, it makes the system more flexible, allowing the optimization of the mix of electricity and thermal energy.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Their availability vary in fact along the day and the year.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Therefore the flexibility allow to reduce the operating costs.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main drawback of this technology is that, to achieve good performances, they typically need to employ ammonia, which is very toxic and flammable.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This drawback resulted in the fact that these applications remained limited to the industrial sector, where it is more practical dealing with dangerous fluids.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most studied configuration is the so-called *compression heat pump with solution cycle* (CHPS) or *compression resorption heat pump* (CRHP), where the compressor is in parallel to the electric pump located between the absorber and the desorber.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration is used to increase the temperature of waste heat since it allow high absorption temperature at lower pressure than compression heat pumps.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Another possible configuration for the absorption compression heat pump is obtained from the combination of a gas-driven absorption heat pump (GAHP) with a vapor-compression heat pump.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration arises from the consideration that both cycles have in common a condenser, a lamination valve, and an evaporator.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main difference between the two is in the compression phase: where the compression heat pump uses an electric compressor, the gas-driven absorption heat pump uses a thermal compressor.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The ACHP is obtained by combining the components that are in common and using the electric and thermal compressor in parallel or in series.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Compression heat pumps use only a single fluid which is a refrigerant.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In contrast, absorption heat pump requires two fluids, a refrigerant and an absorbent able to absorb it.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] By combining the two devices, proper refrigerant absorbent pairs compatible with both the cycles are needed.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] There is a wide choice of refrigerants available for compression heat pumps.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption cycle is the one limiting the choice of the refrigerant.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most common refrigerants for absorption systems are ammonia and water.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Both are good for combined absorption-compression heat pumps.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ammonia has an exceptionally good solubility in water.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This is an important aspect that increases the performance and decreases the size of the device.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] However, its high toxicity and flammability reduces its attractiveness.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Water is a very attractive refrigerant because it is abundant, non-toxic, non-flammable and highly soluble in lithium bromide (LiBr).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main issue with water is that, at the typical heat pump evaporator pressures, it freezes at 0 °C.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This makes water unsuitable for the applications where the cold sink goes below 0 °C, which is the typical winter operating condition of an air source heat pump.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorbent and refrigerant are strictly related to each other.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that ammonia is used as refrigerant, the most common absorbent is water.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that water is used as refrigerant, as previously mentioned, the absorbent is usually LiBr.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ionic liquids have also been proposed as good absorbents, specially for water as refrigerant.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantages of these salts is that they can be used under the conditions at which LiBr solution runs the risk of crystallization and they are less corrosive.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] In adsorption refrigeration, adsorbate vapour molecules, the refrigerant, adsorb onto the surface of a solid instead of dissolving into a liquid.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] Adsorption refrigeration also includes a generation process where refrigerant vapour molecules desorb from the solid.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] In this process, there is no use of CFCs or ammonia; the thermally driven cooling process is environment friendly.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] The characteristics of the adsorbent/refrigerant pair is crucial in determining the system performance of an adsorption refrigeration system.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] The typical system performance indicators for an adsorption refrigeration system are the coefficient of performance and the specific cooling effect.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] The adsorbent is a solid, such as silica gel, activated carbon, or zeolite.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] For example, an adsorption refrigeration device with active carbon fiber as the adsorbent and ammonia as the refrigerant was designed.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] Adsorption refrigeration has been extensively researched in recent years because the technology is often noiseless, non-corrosive and environmentally friendly.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] The heat source for adsorption refrigeration can be fossil fuel, biomass fuel, nuclear fission, geothermal energy, waste heat, or solar thermal energy.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] Adsorption refrigerators are available in the marketplace and are mainly used to produce chilled water from waste heat.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] Gas adsorption heat pumps are not currently available in the UK, but are just being introduced in Europe as small water or ground source packaged units that provide domestic, low-temperature space heating.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] It is very similar to absorption refrigeration (note that the second letter is different) where an absorber absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/adsorption-refrigeration] The refrigerants used in absorption systems are ammonia, water, or methanol, etc, which all experience phase changes between the vapor and liquid states - the same as in vapor compression refrigeration.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] An **air-mixing plenum** (or mixing box) is used in building services engineering and HVAC construction for mixing air from different ductwork systems.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Air streams are mixed to save energy and improve energy efficiency by partially recirculating conditioned air.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] The most common application for an air-mixing plenum is the mixing of *return air* (or *extract air*) with fresh air to provide a supply air mixture for onward distribution to the building or area which the ventilation system is serving.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] The air transferred from the return air stream to the supply air stream is termed *recirculated air*.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] All air not mixed is rejected to the atmosphere as *exhaust air*.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] The mixing plenum normally combines two air streams, and includes for three sets of dampers: one for the fresh air, one for the exhaust air, and a mixing damper between the two air streams.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] The mix of fresh air and recirculated air can thus be adjusted to suit the needs of the building's occupants.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Most systems will use motorized dampers to control the air mixing, and controlled by the building management system (BMS), or controls system.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Typically as the fresh air and exhaust air dampers are driven from 0% open to 100% open, the mixing damper will in turn be driven from 100% open to 0% open, so as to always ensure a constant volume of supply and extract air.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Air supply to a building is generally performed by an air handling unit.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] The process may include filtering, heating, cooling, humidification, or dehumidification, all of which consume energy.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Since building occupants demand less than 100% fresh air, only a fraction of that amount is admitted to the system, with and equal amount of treated air exhausted to the atmosphere; fresh air is mixed with conditioned air in a plenum.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Enhanced controls systems may monitor the return air quality or carbon dioxide concentration in order to automatically modulate the air mix for optimum energy efficiency while maintaining desired fresh air requirements.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Such systems work very well in buildings where the occupancy rate can vary greatly throughout the day, or seasonally.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Additionally, when outside air conditions are such, typically mid-season weather conditions, it may be that ambient temperatures are suitable for free cooling purposes.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] In such conditions the mixing damper will be set to close and the system use full fresh air for optimum energy efficiency.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/air-mixing-plenum] Where fresh air is not required, such as early morning pre-heat or pre-conditioning periods, the mixing damper can be automatically set to full recirculation, again for optimum energy efficiency.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] The **ASHRAE Handbook** is the four-volume flagship publication of the nonprofit technical organization **ASHRAE** (**American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers**).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] This Handbook is considered the most comprehensive and authoritative repository of practical knowledge on the various topics that form the field of heating, ventilation, air-conditioning, and refrigeration (HVAC&R).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] The four volumes are *Fundamentals*, *Refrigeration*, *HVAC Applications* ("Applications"), and *HVAC Systems and Equipment* ("Systems and Equipment").
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] Members of ASHRAE receive the current volume, in both print and CD-ROM form, each year as a basic membership benefit.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] An enhanced electronic version, known as *ASHRAE Handbook Online* is a web-based version updated annually that contains the four latest volumes as well as extra content such as calculations, demonstration videos, and spreadsheets.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] The various versions of the Handbook are typically available to the public via technical, and other, libraries and bookstores.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] The ASHRAE Handbook has had a variety of titles.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] It began in 1922 as the **ASH&VE Guide**.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] In 1973 it became the ASHRAE Handbook, and in 1985 separate publication of inch-pound (I-P) and international system (SI) units versions of the volumes began.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] Stephen Comstock, and the Editor is Mark S.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook is published by ASHRAE from its headquarters in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook's content is created and modified by volunteers via ASHRAE's many Technical Committees (TCs), and then edited and formatted by professional staff at ASHRAE.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] For example, three chapters, in three different volumes, are maintained by TC 5.3, Room Air Distribution.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] Each chapter within a particular volume is reviewed and revised in a repeating four-year cycle; one volume is printed each year.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] In the summer of 2017 the new Fundamentals' volume was released.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] ASHRAE's Handbook Committee maintains an *Authors and Revisers Guide,* which can be obtained freely via the Handbook portion of the ASHRAE Web site.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] While each new or revised chapter manuscript is to be reviewed for technical content by each TC voting and corresponding member before publication, there are often many other pre- and post-publication reviewers.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] For example, members of the Society's Handbook Committee and the College of Fellows review chapters each year.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae-handbook] Reviews, from basic comments to detailed new content, are encouraged from all users of the Handbook and may be submitted through an online commenting system.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The **American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers** (**ASHRAE** /ˈæʃreɪ/ *ASH-ray*) is an American professional association seeking to advance heating, ventilation, air conditioning and refrigeration (HVAC&R) systems design and construction.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE has over 50,000 members in more than 130 countries worldwide.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE's members comprise building services engineers, architects, mechanical contractors, building owners, equipment manufacturers' employees, and others concerned with the design and construction of HVAC&R systems in buildings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The society funds research projects, offers continuing education programs, and develops and publishes technical standards to improve building services engineering, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, and sustainable development.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE was founded in 1894 at a meeting of engineers in New York City, formerly headquartered at 345 East 47th Street (the United Engineering Center), and has held an annual meeting since 1895.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] Until 1954 it was known as the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers (ASHVE); in that year it changed its name to the American Society of Heating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHAE).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] Its current name and organization came from the 1959 merger of ASHAE and the American Society of Refrigerating Engineers (ASRE).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] Despite having 'American' in its name, ASHRAE is a global organization, holding international events.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] In 2012, it rebranded itself with a new logo and tagline: "Shaping Tomorrow's Built Environment Today".
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The ASHRAE Handbook is a four-volume resource for HVAC&R technology and is available in both print and electronic versions.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The volumes are *Fundamentals*, *HVAC Applications*, *HVAC Systems and Equipment*, and *Refrigeration*.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] One of the four volumes is updated each year.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes a set of standards and guidelines relating to HVAC systems and issues, that are often referenced in building codes and used by consulting engineers, mechanical contractors, architects, and government agencies.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] These standards are periodically reviewed, revised and republished.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The society also publishes two magazines: the *ASHRAE Journal* is issued monthly, and *High Performing Buildings Magazine* is published quarterly.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] They contain articles on related technology, information on upcoming meetings, editorials, and case studies of various well-performing buildings.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes books, *ASHRAE Transactions*, and the *International Journal of HVAC&R Research*.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE supported the Streamlining Energy Efficiency for Schools Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] 4092; 113th Congress), a bill that would require the United States Department of Energy to establish a centralized clearinghouse to disseminate information on federal programs, incentives, and mechanisms for financing energy-efficient retrofits and upgrades at schools.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE offers six categories of awards: achievement awards to recognize personal honors; personal awards for general and specific society activities; paper awards; society awards for groups or chapters; chapters and regional awards.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE Fellow is a Membership Grade of Distinction conferred by The College of Fellows of ASHRAE, Inc. to an ASHRAE member with significant publications or innovations and distinguished scientific and engineering background in the fields of heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, ventilation.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The ASHRAE Fellow membership grade is the highest elected grade in ASHRAE.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] ASHRAE has a Hall of Fame honoring "deceased members who have made milestone contributions to the growth of ASHRAE-related technology.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] To demonstrate the Society's commitment to sustainability, ASHRAE renovated its previous headquarters building in Atlanta, Ga.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] After the renovation and occupancy in June 2008, the building received many awards, including an Energy Star rating with a score of 95, a Platinum Certification from USGBC's LEED program, and four Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The current site energy use intensity (EUI) is 35.8 kBtu/Sqft (411 MJ/m2), a 60 percent reduction from the pre-renovation value.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The renovation included the use of a dedicated outdoor air supply (DOAS) system with energy recovery and humidity control; a ground-source heat pump system; and variable refrigerant flow systems with heat recovery.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] The building also serves as a live case study.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] A web-based user interface allowed researchers around the world to extract data from the building to study factors such as energy use and electric power demand, water consumption and indoor air quality.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] In 2018, ASHRAE decided to move their world headquarters, settling on retrofitting a 1970s-era building in Peachtree Corners, suburban Atlanta.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/ashrae] Completed in 2022, the building has been renovated to comply with ASHRAE's own standards, including ASHRAE 90.1, and the organization has the goal of operating the building at net-zero energy, powered by a large on-site solar array.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:absorption-refrigerator/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
